Introduction

A new feature set has been created, based on another reference set, and which does not transform the counts of the intermediate entities. The new files appear to be in line with our requested changes sent by email on 09-11-2017.

# Create the positive set
count_pos = read.csv("count_pos.csv", stringsAsFactors = F)
diversity_pos = read.csv("diversity_pos.csv", stringsAsFactors = F)
pos = merge(count_pos, diversity_pos, by = intersect(colnames(count_pos), colnames(diversity_pos)))
pos$goldstandard = "VALID"

# Create the negative set
count_neg = read.csv("count_neg.csv", stringsAsFactors = F)
diversity_neg = read.csv("diversity_neg.csv", stringsAsFactors = F)
neg = merge(count_neg, diversity_neg, by = intersect(colnames(count_neg), colnames(diversity_neg)))
neg$goldstandard = "INVALID"

There appears to be a difference in the number of rows between the diversity and the count negative files. This difference becomes more pronounced when they are merged. Furthermore, the rows are not unique. We perform our further experiments with the unique instances of the negative file.

all = rbind.fill(pos, neg)
all[is.na(all)] = 0
# Some columns are empty, meaning their sum is 0. Others are not relevant as features. These are also removed
all$direct = as.logical(all$direct)
goldstandard = all$goldstandard
exclusion_columns = c("Drug", "Disease", "Drugbank.ID", "Disease.ID", "drug_ids", "disease_ids", "goldstandard")
feature_set = all[,-which(colnames(all) %in% exclusion_columns)]
feature_set = feature_set[,-which(colnames(feature_set) %in% names(which(colSums(feature_set) == 0)))]

Feature correlations

To identify which features correlate with each other, we create a correlation matrix.

# Create a correlation matrix
input_matrix = as.matrix(cor(feature_set))
feature_cors = arrange(melt(input_matrix), -abs(value))
feature_combos = feature_cors[!feature_cors$value > 0.9, ]

# Remove duplicate values from correlation matrix
feature_combos$A = NA
feature_combos$B = NA
feature_combos$Var1 = as.character(feature_combos$Var1)
feature_combos$Var2 = as.character(feature_combos$Var2)
for(i in 1:nrow(feature_combos)){
  feature_combos[i,c("A", "B")] = feature_combos[i, order(feature_combos[i, c("Var1", "Var2")])]
}
feature_combos = unique(feature_combos[,c("A", "B", "value")])
feature_combos = feature_combos[order(feature_combos$value, decreasing = T), ]
hist(feature_combos$value, main = "Histogram of correlations between features", xlab = "Correlation coefficient", xlim = c(-0.1,1), breaks = seq(-0.1,1, 0.05))

colnames(feature_combos) = c("A", "B", "correlation")

Machine learning

Same as previously, we apply the machine learning algorithm to the dataset. First we apply the random forest algorithm

rf_model = train(x = feature_set, y = goldstandard, method = "rf", 
              trControl=trainControl(method="cv",number=10, classProbs = TRUE, 
              savePredictions = TRUE, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary),
              prox=TRUE, allowParallel=TRUE, metric = "ROC")

Equally sized classification

Because there is a ~ 2:1 class imbalance between the two classes, we examine how performance is affected when there is an equal distribution between the two classes.

createBalancedSet = function(df, n, pos_class = "VALID"){
  balanced = rbind(df[sample(row.names(df[df$goldstandard == pos_class, ]), n),], 
                   df[sample(row.names(df[!df$goldstandard == pos_class, ]), n),])
  return(balanced)}

freqs = table(goldstandard)

equal_set = createBalancedSet(all, min(freqs))
equal_standard = equal_set$goldstandard
equal_set = equal_set[,-which(colnames(equal_set) %in% exclusion_columns)]

equal_rf_model = train(x = equal_set, y = equal_standard, method = "rf", 
              trControl=trainControl(method="cv",number=10, classProbs = TRUE, 
              savePredictions = TRUE, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary),
              prox=TRUE, allowParallel=TRUE, metric = "ROC")

kable(equal_rf_model$results[equal_rf_model$results$mtry == equal_rf_model$bestTune$mtry, c("ROC", "Sens", "Spec")])
ROC Sens Spec
2 0.9439602 0.856743 0.8858776

Label scrambling check

The labels are scrambled by random ones, again with an equal distribution to see whether performance changes

scrambled_standard = sample(c("VALID", "INVALID"), 2*min(freqs), replace = T)

scrambled_rf_model = train(x = equal_set, y = scrambled_standard, method = "rf", 
              trControl=trainControl(method="cv",number=10, classProbs = TRUE, 
              savePredictions = TRUE, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary),
              prox=TRUE, allowParallel=TRUE, metric = "ROC")

Internal classification check

Another check is performed by quantifying whether the classifier is able to group the negative set itself, or the positive.

neg_scrambled_standard = sample(c("VALID", "INVALID"), nrow(neg), replace = T)

neg_input = neg[,-which(colnames(neg) %in% exclusion_columns)]
neg_input[is.na(neg_input)] = 0
neg_input$direct = as.logical(neg_input$direct)

neg_rf_model = train(x = neg_input, y = neg_scrambled_standard, method = "rf", 
              trControl=trainControl(method="cv",number=10, classProbs = TRUE, 
              savePredictions = TRUE, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary),
              prox=TRUE, allowParallel=TRUE, metric = "ROC")

pos_input = pos[,-which(colnames(pos) %in% exclusion_columns)]
pos_input[is.na(pos_input)] = 0
pos_input$direct = as.logical(pos_input$direct)

pos_rf_model = train(x = pos_input, y = pos_scrambled_standard, method = "rf", 
              trControl=trainControl(method="cv",number=10, classProbs = TRUE, 
              savePredictions = TRUE, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary),
              prox=TRUE, allowParallel=TRUE, metric = "ROC")

kable(neg_rf_model$results[neg_rf_model$results$mtry == neg_rf_model$bestTune$mtry, c("ROC", "Sens", "Spec")])
